<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Thu 7 Feb 2008
Source: Daily Post [edited]
<http://www.dailypost.co.uk/farming-north-wales/farming-news/2008/02/07/bluetongue-zones-wider-as-more-cases-found-55578-20444553/>


Bluetongue zones widen as more cases found
------------------------------------------
Britain's bluetongue protection and surveillance zones was this week
[4-8 Feb 2008] extended after new cases were discovered during
pre-movement testing. The infected animals, in the south east of
England, were found as a result of the testing regime put in place
during the vector-free period. Bluetongue zones were subsequently
expanded further into Sussex and Dorset.

Evidence suggests the animals were infected before start of the
vector-free period but symptoms were so mild the cases were not
detected. The UK outbreak total now stands at 70.

Further similar cases are expected in the coming weeks as more
animals are tested prior to being moved, said rural ministry Defra.
It has ordered 22.5m doses of vaccine for bluetongue serotype 8
including 2.5m doses for disease-free Wales from animal health firm
Intervet. The first 2.25m doses, expected in May [2008], will be used
in the current protection zone.

As further batches arrive, the focus will shift westwards and along
the south coast due to the risk of the virus spreading from France,
according to the NFU. The strategy depends on the initial order for
2.25m doses arriving on time and no cases of bluetongue outside the
protection zone.

The NFU fears there may not be enough vaccine to go round if the
disease takes hold before vaccination is effective. For the policy to
work, 80 percent of susceptible stock must be vaccinated.

With 60m livestock in the UK and the need to vaccinate cattle twice,
the NFU council says the numbers don't stack up and has called for an
urgent review.

[Byline: Andrew Forgrave]

