******
[2]
Date: Fri 8 Feb 2008
Source: The Guardian [edited]
<http://www.guardian.co.uk/environment/2008/feb/08/ruralaffairs1?gusrc=rss&feed=networkfront>


New bluetongue case in Watford
-----------------------------------------------------
A bluetongue protection zone has been set up in Greater London after
a new case of the disease was discovered in Watford, the government
announced today.

The Department for the Environment, Food and Rural Affairs (Defra)
said the 20km [12.4-mile] zone was put in place after a cow in
Watford tested positive for the disease. The zone covers parts of
north and west London, as well as parts of Buckinghamshire and Hertfordshire.

In addition, 2 cases have also been found inside the existing
bluetongue protection zone covering much of East Anglia and parts of
Kent. That zone has now been extended into Surrey and Cambridgeshire,
said a Defra spokeswoman.

The spokeswoman said the 3 cattle were infected before the start of
the "vector-free period" on 20 Dec 2007, the point at which it was
judged there was a low risk of the disease spreading because the
weather was too cold for the midges that spread it.

There are 75 confirmed cases of the virus, which is fatal to animals
such as sheep and cows, in the UK. The cases were identified by
routine testing, which is required before animals can be moved out of
the protection and surveillance zones. Defra said further cases could
be identified in the coming weeks.

Bluetongue was first confirmed in the UK on 28 Sep 2007 in East
Anglia. All other cases have been confined to the south-east of England.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The most recent update of the Declaration of a Protection zone and
Surveillance zone, with map, is available at
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/bluetongue/pdf/declaration-btv-pzsz080208.pdf>.


The interpretation of official data on detected BT-positive animals
during the so-called "non-vector period" is debatable. If, as
suggested in the above report, the infection had taken place before
the start of the period, these are not new cases but just reflections
of last year's (2007) outbreak. According to this moderator's
understanding, to detect virus/vector activity during the declared
"no-vector season," at least one of the following should be met:

1. Clinical cases observed, confirmed by virus isolation (during the
viraemia);
2. Virus isolated from subclinical cases (possible by weekly blood
sampling in sentinels);
3. Infected vectors trapped;
4. Seroconversion clearly demonstrated in sentinels which have been
tested negative at the start of the season and became positive later.

It seems that the same doubts on the out-of-season BTV-8 activity are
encountered in continental Europe, e.g., France: subscriber Susan
Baekeland has kindly provided data of the French Ministry of
Agriculture, reporting that as of 6 Feb 2008, a total of 16 677 BT
accumulated cases have been listed, including 2 new ones which are
reported "as they involve an extension of an exclusion zone." They
were in Creuse (Sardent) and in Puy-de-Dome (Condat en Combraille),
south-central France.

An official view of EU's BT experts panel on the current situation --
"active or not?!" -- will be helpful.

In addition, an update on the BTV-8 situation in more southern areas
is in need; this, in view of reports (thanks to submitter Sabrine
Zentis!), on its further spread in northern Spain (Cantabria) and on
the detection of a positive cow in the south-western Swiss canton
Wallis, close to the lake of Geneva. - Mod.AS]
